As expected, Alaska did fall back under 450 thousand b/d last week, while the L48 held flat. That sets the first of the final four data points at 12,100. We would now need to see two of the last three observations at 12,300 (with the other at 12,200) for this to cross into bin 3.

Alaska's production did tip over the 450 mark last week, pushing the US total to 12,200 thousand b/d (rounded). We are flirting with the boundary of bin 2 as the question finishes up. There are 4 unreported weeks remaining. Breaking into bin 3 requires a one unit increment from the L48 during the next four reports while Alaska holds above 450. It is very possible, but there are a lot of ways for things to miss. My biggest concern at this point is that Alaska's production is hoovering right at the edge. Preliminary data suggests that we saw a very slight decrease this week. Even a 1,000 b/d decrease would render this question over. We may know the answer when the next data point is posted later this week.
The production number posted today for the week ending 12/2 was 12,125. The chances of reaching 12,225 by 12/30 have increased, IMO.

There are now 7 data points remaining until this question closes. Preliminary data from Alaska shows that the next data point will cross 450 and be rounded to 500. This should bring the US total to 12.2 MMBOPD. It's still not clear to me if the L48 number will move up to 11.8 before the end of the year. But, the odds are decent.
The week ending 9 December must be 12,220 or over for this question to have any possibility of getting to bin 3. That is 2 releases away.

The data from 11/4 shows that production from Alaska was 446, which was rounded down to 400. With an increase of just 5,000 barrels per day from Alaska, the total production for the US would be reported as 12,200. As winter production continues to rise, it is very likely to cross within the next few weeks. If L48 production holds at the current rate of 11,700, we only need to see an increase of 100 thousand b/d from the L48, for a single week, to reach 12,225.

With production levels falling slightly in the continental US and with Alaska staying around 430 MBOPD so far in October, the chances of crossing 12.2 million BOPD are reduced. However, because of the way that these numbers are reported, there is still a substantial possibility of reaching bin 3 before the end of the year.
It will be interesting to see how quickly production recovers from hurricane Ian. I'm betting it won't reach 12,225 before Dec 30.

Production fell slightly to 12,050 k b/d for the week ending 9/30/22. I'm assuming the cause was Gulf of Mexico wells shut in due to hurricane Ian. If so it should recover quickly. Still, it appears a little less likely to surpass 12,200 k b/d before the end of the year. I'll move a few chips down to the 11,825 to 12,200 bin. [Note: Since June 2018 they have always rounded to the nearest 25 k b/d. A rounding error might well change the outcome.]

The L48 production number only needs to increase to by one unit for bin 3 to prevail. It seems unlikely that we will see the rapid increase necessary to reach above bin 3 within the time remaining.

So far it's been a quiet Atlantic hurricane season. A major hurricane in the Gulf of Mexico is a wild card that could hold production below the favored bin (12,200 to 12,600 thousand b/d). I'll increase to 3 to 1 the odds of exceeding 12,200 (and reaching bin 3). If and when a hurricane threatens I'll dial that back.

This article on oilprice.com is four months old now, but the arguments are the same today. See <https://oilprice.com/Energy/Energy-General/Why-Isnt-US-Shale-Production-Soaring.html>. To quote:

Upweighting bin #2 in light of the apparent (and to me, unexpected) total stagnation of production growth over the past month. Prices / outlook don’t often get much better than this. If significant growth isn’t happening in the next few weeks, perhaps it won’t happen at all. Economic slow-down won’t help.

Highest ever production was 13m but current is 11.9m and steadily climbing each week. recent forecasts that prices are going to level off or slightly decline suggests slightly less pressure to increase production.

Production growth has clearly kicked off and stabilized over the past month+. At present growth rates, would expect it to take only a couple more months at most to exceed bin #2. The next big question remains: at what point in time will production growth start noticeably tapering to a new, higher equilibrium level? Once production begins, anything less than an epic crash will not be enough to shut in / truncate newly tapped production volumes, and pre-price climb (~1H21) baseline decline does not seem to be high, so I’m making an “informed assumption” in my forecasts on this question that once production rises above any given level (and allowing for small short-term fluctuations of ~100 kb/d or less), there is no credible scenario within our timeframe where production will ever “peak” and fall significantly lower than any recently observed / established level. In short: the ultimate maximum we are forecasting is very likely to express close to the end date, unless there is soon a major (and extremely unlikely) turn-around in prices. There is still a very wide range of outcomes in play!

With producers having geared up for further production in the short term with the price incentive, I believe they will attempt to make use of the additional capacity. However, I believe they won't be able to make long term capacity extensions to their facilities. Hence don't see a significant spike beyond recent max. capacity. I don't believe the opportunity will extend much beyond the next few months, as existing producers elsewhere will have the same idea and production will reach a new equilibrium.

Global demand expected to increase by about 1%, most questions are centered around the compensation for Russia's exports. USA is almost self-sufficient with 3% import from Russia, likely covered by domestic increase. Release of strategic reserves to compensate world demand should not affect the US production. Forecasts were released by EIA for 22/23 prior to the war, but remain a good reference for capacity increase. Hence despite the current world situation, we don't believe that a massive increase of production will happen (on a 4-week rolling basis) in such a short time horizon as 2022. That said, the pricing levels seem to support local initiatives in particular in the domain of shale oil. The forecast is center around a linear growth of ~8% corresponding to both the last 12m observed growth and the EIA projections, with a smaller chance to come lower (target metric is the "max"), and limited chances of large increase given the production constraints. Also OPEC's recent announcement of production increase will calm US entrepreneurship down.

The usual peak oil production statistic (base rate) wavers around 7.5k or so. It can go up all the way to around 13k already, and given the state of decoupling from Russia, US domestic production is likely to go higher than pre-invasion levels. Part of this might be offset by external sources, so I drop the estimate down a bit to around 29%.
